{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11702"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11702"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.19,0.03,0.23,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110590"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4317"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92835"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1599"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42649"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110590"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents with a six month history of increasing difficulty in urinating. He is able to start without any problems, but has to strain to pass urine. Whilst it does take increasing longer, he feels that he can empty his bladder. There is some dribbling at the end of micturition. He does not have any frequency and he only gets up to void at night if he has a large quantity of liquid to drink in the evenings. He passes bowel motions daily without episodes of incontinence. His medical history is unremarkable, apart from a pelvic fracture from a motorbike crash when he was 21. The physical examination, including a digital rectal examination, is unremarkable and his bladder is not distended.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prostate specific antigen","CT abdomen and pelvis","Trans-rectal ultrasound-guided biopsy (TRUS)","Urethroscopy","Retrograde urethrogram"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms is an urethral stricture. Urethral stricture is a narrowing or constriction of the urethra, which can occur due to injury, infection, or other underlying conditions. In this case, it is quite possible that the stricture is the result of trauma. Whilst the information is not provided in the stem, he may well have had a sexually transmitted infection (STI), and this has been complicated by stricture formation. Most cases of urethral stricture formation are secondary to perineal trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the most appropriate next step would be \u003Cstrong\u003Eurethroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows direct visualisation of the urethra and can be used to confirm the diagnosis of urethral stricture as well as to provide a definitive treatment (ie dilatation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrans-rectal ultrasound-guided biopsy (TRUS)\u003C/strong\u003E is a procedure that uses an ultrasound probe inserted into the rectum to visualise the prostate and guide the biopsy needle to obtain tissue samples for examination. A TRUS is primarily used to detect prostate cancer or other prostate-related issues, by obtaining tissue samples of the prostate, and it is not specific to urethral stricture. It would be unusual for a 32-year-old man to have urinary symptoms due to prostate-related bladder neck outflow obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretrograde urethrogram\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to diagnose urethral stricture and other urethral disorders. Whilst this procedure could define the site and likely cause of a urethral obstruction, it is only diagnostic, whereas urethroscopy has a therapeutic element.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E prostate specific antigen (PSA) test \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be quite an appropriate investigation if this patient was much older and the cause of his urinary symptoms was thought to be prostatic in origin. However, that is not the case here and a PSA would be of little value.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E CT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E might provide useful information about any possible mass lesion within the pelvis or abdomen, but in this case it is very unlikely that the cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms are from within the abdominal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urethral stricture formation secondary to an STI must be considered in young men presenting with difficulty in voiding.","Urethroscopy is both a diagnostic and therapeutic tool for urethral strictures."],"references":["Wason SE, Monfared S, Ionson A, et al. Ureteroscopy. [Updated 2024 Apr 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560556/","Wessells H, Morey A, Souter L, Rahimi L, Vanni A. Urethral Stricture Disease Guideline Amendment (2023). J Urol. 2023 Jul;210(1):64-71. doi: 10.1097/JU.0000000000003482. Epub 2023 Apr 25. PMID: 37096574. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37096574/","Abdeen BM, Leslie SW, Badreldin AM. Urethral Strictures. 2024 Oct 29. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 33231967. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33231967/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92835"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11702"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92835"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T18:50:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T18:50:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4317"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110590"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduatin